# Domain Layer -- AuntiesRecipe.Domain

The innermost layer. Contains **only** business entities, value objects, and enums. This project has ZERO project references and ZERO NuGet package references beyond the base SDK.

## Allowed

- Plain C# classes / records / structs for entities and value objects
- Enums representing domain concepts (e.g., `OrderStatus`)
- Navigation properties (typed as `ICollection<T>` or concrete `List<T>`)
- Computed read-only properties derived from entity state
- Simple domain validation inside entity constructors or methods

## Forbidden

- `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` or any EF Core attribute (`[Key]`, `[Required]`, `[Column]`, etc.)
- `using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations` -- use Fluent API in Infrastructure instead
- `using Microsoft.AspNetCore.*`
- Any reference to Application, Infrastructure, or Web namespaces
- Any I/O (file, network, database)
- Static service locator patterns
- Dependency injection (no constructor-injected services)

## Examples

```csharp
// GOOD -- pure entity
namespace AuntiesRecipe.Domain.Entities;

public class Order
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string PickupName { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public OrderStatus Status { get; set; }
    public List<OrderItem> Items { get; set; } = [];
    public decimal Total => Items.Sum(i => i.LineTotal);
}

// BAD -- EF annotation leaking into Domain
using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;

public class Order
{
    [Key]
    public int Id { get; set; }

    [Required, MaxLength(100)]
    public string PickupName { get; set; } = string.Empty;
}
```

## Adding a New Entity

1. Create the class in `Domain/Entities/`
2. Configure it via Fluent API in `Infrastructure/Data/AppDbContext.OnModelCreating`
3. Add a `DbSet<T>` in `AppDbContext`
4. Generate an EF Core migration from the Infrastructure project
